Sure thing! To find and count valid parentheses in Java, you can use a stack to keep track of the opening parentheses. Here's a simple way to do it:

1. Initialize a stack.
2. Iterate through each character in the string.
3. If you encounter an opening parenthesis '(', push it onto the stack.
4. If you encounter a closing parenthesis ')', check if the stack is empty or the top of the stack is not an opening parenthesis. If either condition is true, it means the parentheses are invalid, so return 0. Otherwise, pop the top of the stack.
5. After iterating through the string, the size of the stack will give you the number of unmatched opening parentheses. Subtract this from the total number of characters to get the number of valid pairs.

Here's a quick implementation:

```java
public int countValidParentheses(String s) {
    Stack<Character> stack = new Stack<>();
    int count = 0;

    for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
        if (c == '(') {
            stack.push(c);
        } else if (c == ')') {
            if (!stack.isEmpty() && stack.peek() == '(') {
                stack.pop();
                count++;
            } else {
                return 0; // Invalid parentheses
            }
        }
    }

    return s.length() - stack.size(); // Total length minus unmatched open parentheses
}
```

This function will return the number of valid parentheses pairs. If the input string has any unbalanced parentheses, it will return 0.

